If you really need a way to &#39;rate limit&#39; one particular IP and you want an Apache module for it then this might be for you: &lt;br&gt;
https://wiki.debian.org/en/Apache/mod_evasive &lt;br&gt;

mod_evasive is a module that detects possible attack patterns on the network similar to an IPS (intrusion prevention system). &lt;br&gt;
A basic explanation about what an IPS does it [right here][1].

To setup the module run 

    sudo apt-get install libapache2-mod-evasive 
Then activate the module with

    sudo a2enmod evasive 
Verify the installation by running

     sudo apachectl -M | grep evasive
Expected output:  *evasive20_module (shared)* &lt;br&gt;
Now we create a new folder for our apache module so it can write logs to it.

    sudo mkdir /var/log/mod_evasive
    sudo chown www-data:root /var/log/mod_evasive 
Let&#39;s edit the config of mod_evasive. I use [nano][2] for this example

    sudo nano /etc/apache2/mods-available/evasive.conf
*Please note: Never edit a module configuration in /apache2/mods-enabled/ use /apache2/mods-available/ instead. The example provided above is correct.* &lt;br&gt;
This is an example configuration:

     &lt;IfModule mod_evasive20.c&gt; 
     DOSHashTableSize 3097 
     DOSPageCount 2 
     DOSSiteCount 50 
     DOSPageInterval 1 
     DOSSiteInterval 1 
     DOSBlockingPeriod 10 
     DOSEmailNotify email@yourdomain.com 
     DOSSystemCommand &quot;echo +%s &gt; /proc/net/xt_recent/badguys&quot; or block them with iptables &quot;su root -c &#39;/sbin/iptables -A INPUT -s %s -j DROP&#39;&quot; ##command that will be sent to the system - %s = attackers ip
     DOSLogDir &quot;/var/log/mod_evasive&quot; 
     DOSWhitelist 127.0.0.1
     &lt;/IfModule&gt;
If you want to get email notifications via sendmail use

    sudo ln -s /usr/bin/mail /bin/mail 
&lt;br&gt;
Finally just restart apache using

     sudo systemctl restart apache2
&lt;br&gt;
To limit the module to one location, use 

    &lt;Directory /var/www/test/&gt;
      &lt;IfModule moduleLimitedToTest&gt;
       ... do something with module
      &lt;/IfModule&gt;
    &lt;/Directory&gt;
More on how to use containers can be found [here][3]. You could place this into a site/virtualhost config. This is explained [here][4].
&lt;br&gt;
*Though I&#39;d strongly recommend the same thing as Olaf Kock.*


  [1]: http://www.ciscopress.com/articles/article.asp?p=1722559
  [2]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_nano
  [3]: http://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/sections.html
  [4]: https://httpd.apache.org/docs/2.4/vhosts/examples.html

